## Migration: `TimedExecutor` (.NET Framework → .NET 8)

### Pattern Classification

This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. The code spawns a thread, waits for a deadline, then forcibly kills it via `Thread.Abort()`. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports preemptive thread termination.

### Why It Breaks

| API | .NET 8 Behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by the runtime |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative timeout.
    /// The work delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/>
    /// for cancellation to be timely.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Overload for callers that cannot pass a CancellationToken into their work.
    // WARNING: If work ignores the token, it continues running in the background
    // until it finishes on its own — there is no way to forcibly stop it.
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Uses the thread pool; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | Cancellation-aware wait (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) | Cooperative cancellation replaces forced abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cancellation is cooperative |
| Manual `error` variable | `Task<T>` propagates exceptions | Task infrastructure handles marshalling exceptions to the caller |

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE — caller cannot observe cancellation
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeExpensiveResult(), 
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER — preferred: pass the token so work can stop promptly
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    // Check the token at regular checkpoints
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        ProcessChunk(i);
    }
    return FinalResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

1. **Work must cooperate.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation only works if the delegate checks the token. The token-less overload lets you time out the *wait*, but the work keeps running on a thread-pool thread until it finishes naturally. This is a fire-and-forget leak if the work never returns.

2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds an internal timer. The `using` statement above prevents timer leaks.

3. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures we only convert *our* timeout into `TimeoutException`. An `OperationCanceledException` from some other token propagates normally.

4. **Blocking on async code.** `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` blocks the calling thread. If you can make the caller `async`, prefer:
   ```csharp
   public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
       Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
       try
       {
           return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                            .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
       }
       catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
       {
           throw new TimeoutException(
               $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
       }
   }
   ```

5. **Uncooperative third-party code.** If you truly need to kill work that can't check a token (e.g., a native call), move it to a child **process** and call `Process.Kill()`. This is the only reliable forced-termination mechanism in modern .NET.
